+--------------------------------------------------------------------+
| Browser Wars Declared Over?                                        |
|   from the everyone-just-afraid-of-losing dept.                    |
|   posted by ScuttleMonkey on Wednesday April 18, @13:25 (The Intern|
|   http://slashdot.org/article.pl?sid=07/04/18/1510250              |
+--------------------------------------------------------------------+

[0]Kelson writes to mention Microsoft, Mozilla, Opera and Google took the
stage this week at the Web 2.0 expo and in addition to discussing
pressing issues have declared their intent to [1]avoid another browser
war. All the panelists agreed that security was the largest concern
currently facing browser developers. "Brendan Eich, the chief technology
officer at Mozilla, said that security was hard and always will be. 'I
don't think we should take security lightly; it's an end-to-end problem
and we have to step outside the current model to win on this front,' he
said. For his part, Chris Wetherell, a software engineer at Google, said
one of the scenarios that kept him awake at night was offline access to
the browser and what that meant from a security perspective, particularly
on the user-to-user front."

Discuss this story at:
    http://slashdot.org/comments.pl?sid=07/04/18/1510250

Links:
    0. http://www.alternativebrowseralliance.com/
    1. http://www.eweek.com/article2/0,1759,2114880,00.asp


